1. CLOCK NETWORK BALANCING RESULTS
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
TritonCTS inserted a network of balanced clock buffers to minimize skew 
and latency across all 64 sequential flip-flops in the design:

* Target Clock Power Domain:  clk
* Longest Path Latency:       0.49 ns  (Farthest register pin '_1512_/CLK')
* Shortest Path Latency:      0.44 ns  (Closest register pin '_1482_/CLK')
* Clock Reconvergence Pessimism Removal (CRPR): -0.03 ns

Final Balanced Clock Skew:
============================================================================
Skew = (Longest Latency - Shortest Latency) + CRPR
Skew = (0.49 ns - 0.44 ns) - 0.03 ns = 0.02 ns (20 ps)
============================================================================
Status: Excellent. A clock skew of 20 ps ensures that data launch and 
        capture windows across the entire macro remain perfectly synchronized.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. PHYSICAL CTS OVERHEAD ANALYSIS (The Placement vs. CTS Trade-off)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Building the physical clock tree requires adding clock buffer cells to drive 
the heavy capacitance of the synchronized registers. This introduced a 
standard physical overhead trade-off:

* Silicon Area:   Increased from 9600 u^2 to 9826 u^2 (~37% core utilization)
* Total Power:    Increased from 2.07 mW to 2.33 mW (Typical Corner)

Analysis: The 15.7% total power draw allocated to sequential clock buffers 
is highly efficient for an AXI-interfaced cryptographic structure.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. POST-CTS TIMING STABILITY
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
* Worst Setup Slack (Post-CTS):  +4.00 ns (Virtually unchanged from placement)
* Worst Hold Slack (Post-CTS):   +0.20 ns (Completely positive and secure)

Result: The clock tree buffer placement successfully minimized skew without 
degrading the arrival margins of critical data paths.
